---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Brand from "../components/Brand.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="How to Remove Metadata from Photos — StripMeta Guide"
  description="Learn what EXIF metadata is, what data photos typically carry and when you might want to remove it before sharing, and how to strip it in seconds using StripMeta, entirely in your browser."
>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="w-full text-center flex flex-col gap-3">
    <div
      class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-base-content/35"
    >
      Guide
    </div>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">
      Your photos reveal more than you think.
    </h1>
  </section>

  <!-- Hero body + TOC -->
  <div class="w-full flex flex-col gap-6 lg:flex-row lg:items-center lg:gap-10">
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 flex-1 w-full">
      <p class="text-base-content/60 leading-relaxed text-left">
        Every image you take or screenshot you capture is quietly embedded with
        data about where you were, what device you used, and when. Here's what
        that data is, and how to remove it before sharing.
      </p>
      <div class="flex justify-center">
        <a href="/" class="btn btn-brand btn-sm">Use StripMeta now →</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- TOC -->
    <nav
      aria-label="Page contents"
      class="w-full lg:w-auto lg:shrink-0 rounded-xl border border-base-300 px-5 py-4"
    >
      <p
        class="text-[0.65rem] font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-base-content/35 mb-3"
      >
        Contents
      </p>
      <ol class="flex flex-col gap-1.5 list-none m-0 p-0">
        {
          [
            ["#what-is-metadata", "What is photo metadata?"],
            ["#real-example", "A real example"],
            ["#why-it-matters", "Why it's a privacy problem"],
            ["#how-it-removes", "How StripMeta removes it"],
            ["#how-to-use", "How to use StripMeta"],
          ].map(([href, label], i) => (
            <li class="flex items-baseline gap-2.5">
              <span class="text-[0.65rem] tabular-nums text-base-content/30 w-3 shrink-0">
                {i + 1}.
              </span>
              <a
                href={href}
                class="text-sm text-base-content/60 hover:text-base-content/90 transition-colors underline-offset-2 hover:underline"
              >
                {label}
              </a>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ol>
    </nav>
  </div>

  <!-- What is metadata -->
  <section id="what-is-metadata" class="w-full flex flex-col gap-6">
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">What is photo metadata?</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-base-content/65 leading-relaxed">
        Every digital photo carries two things: the image you see, and a silent
        passenger of structured data attached to it. This data, stored in
        standardised formats like <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exif"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="underline underline-offset-2 decoration-base-content/30 hover:decoration-base-content/60 transition-colors"
          ><strong class="text-base-content/80">EXIF</strong></a
        > (Exchangeable Image File Format), <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPTC_Information_Interchange_Model"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="underline underline-offset-2 decoration-base-content/30 hover:decoration-base-content/60 transition-colors"
          ><strong class="text-base-content/80">IPTC</strong></a
        >, and <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extensible_Metadata_Platform"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="underline underline-offset-2 decoration-base-content/30 hover:decoration-base-content/60 transition-colors"
          ><strong class="text-base-content/80">XMP</strong></a
        >, is written automatically by your phone or camera at the moment you
        press the shutter. It was designed to help photo software organise and
        interpret images correctly, but that also means every photo you share
        carries a detailed record of the moment it was taken.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-base-content/65 leading-relaxed">
        It isn't visible in the image itself, it's not shown by default in file
        managers or photo viewers, and it travels with the photo wherever it
        goes. Anyone receiving or seeing that photo online can view or extract
        it easily using freely available tools.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-base-content/65 leading-relaxed">
        For most people under usual circumstances that is not a real problem,
        but in some situations you'd want to sanitise your photos or screenshots
        before sharing them — that is where you might want to use a tool like <Brand
        />. Screenshots typically carry a smaller set of metadata (e.g. device
        model, OS version and a timestamp) — but it is often the combination of
        data that makes you trackable, not a single piece of information on its
        own.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 p-4 flex gap-3">
        <span class="text-2xl shrink-0">📍</span>
        <div>
          <p class="font-semibold text-sm">
            <a
              href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exif#GPS_tags"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
              class="underline underline-offset-2 decoration-base-content/30 hover:decoration-base-content/60 transition-colors"
              >GPS coordinates</a
            >
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-base-content/55 mt-1 leading-relaxed">
            Precise latitude, longitude, and altitude at the moment the photo
            was taken. Sometimes includes direction and speed of travel. Often
            accurate up to within a few metres.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 p-4 flex gap-3">
        <span class="text-2xl shrink-0">📱</span>
        <div>
          <p class="font-semibold text-sm">Device identity</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-base-content/55 mt-1 leading-relaxed">
            Manufacturer and model name, and for cameras a <em
              >body serial number</em
            > — the physical hardware serial that stays the same across every photo
            the device ever takes, making it possible to link shots from different
            sources to the same camera.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 p-4 flex gap-3">
        <span class="text-2xl shrink-0">🔧</span>
        <div>
          <p class="font-semibold text-sm">Software & editing history</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-base-content/55 mt-1 leading-relaxed">
            The operating system version, camera app, and editing software used,
            usually including version numbers. Adobe Lightroom, Snapseed, iOS
            Photos, and others all leave traces.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 p-4 flex gap-3">
        <span class="text-2xl shrink-0">🕐</span>
        <div>
          <p class="font-semibold text-sm">Timestamps</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-base-content/55 mt-1 leading-relaxed">
            The exact date and time the photo was captured, and when it was last
            modified. Some formats also record the local timezone offset.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 p-4 flex gap-3">
        <span class="text-2xl shrink-0">📷</span>
        <div>
          <p class="font-semibold text-sm">Camera settings</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-base-content/55 mt-1 leading-relaxed">
            ISO speed, aperture, shutter speed, focal length, flash state, white
            balance, metering mode, and lens information — the full technical
            context of every shot, like a fingerprint.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 p-4 flex gap-3">
        <span class="text-2xl shrink-0">🏷️</span>
        <div>
          <p class="font-semibold text-sm">Authorship & copyright</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-base-content/55 mt-1 leading-relaxed">
            Photographer name, copyright string, caption, keywords, and contact
            details — often added automatically by camera apps or synced from
            your Apple ID or Google account.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Real example -->
  <section id="real-example" class="w-full flex flex-col gap-4">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">A real example</h2>
    <p class="text-base-content/65 leading-relaxed">
      Here is the kind of metadata embedded in an ordinary photo taken on a
      modern smartphone:
    </p>
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 overflow-hidden">
      <div
        class="bg-base-200/60 px-4 py-2 text-xs font-mono text-base-content/40 border-b border-base-300"
      >
        vacation.jpg - embedded metadata
      </div>
      <div
        class="p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-loose grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-x-8"
      >
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-0.5">
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-base-content/35 shrink-0 w-36">GPS Latitude</span
            ><span class="text-red-500 dark:text-red-400 font-medium"
              >48.8566° N</span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-base-content/35 shrink-0 w-36">GPS Longitude</span
            ><span class="text-red-500 dark:text-red-400 font-medium"
              >2.3522° E</span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-base-content/35 shrink-0 w-36">GPS Altitude</span
            ><span class="text-red-500 dark:text-red-400 font-medium"
              >35.2 m</span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-base-content/35 shrink-0 w-36">Date / Time</span
            ><span class="text-orange-500 dark:text-orange-400 font-medium"
              >2024-07-14 14:32:08</span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-base-content/35 shrink-0 w-36">Offset Time</span
            ><span class="text-orange-500 dark:text-orange-400 font-medium"
              >+02:00</span
            >
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-0.5 mt-2 sm:mt-0">
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-base-content/35 shrink-0 w-36">Make</span><span
              class="text-base-content/70">Apple</span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-base-content/35 shrink-0 w-36">Model</span><span
              class="text-base-content/70">iPhone 15 Pro</span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-base-content/35 shrink-0 w-36"
              >Image Unique ID</span
            ><span class="text-orange-500 dark:text-orange-400 font-medium"
              >C8JFNF3TMQXF</span
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-base-content/35 shrink-0 w-36">Software</span
            ><span class="text-base-content/70">iOS 17.5.1</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-base-content/35 shrink-0 w-36">F-Number</span
            ><span class="text-base-content/70">f/1.78</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-base-content/35 shrink-0 w-36">ISO Speed</span
            ><span class="text-base-content/70">64</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div
        class="px-4 py-2 bg-base-200/40 border-t border-base-300 text-xs text-base-content/40"
      >
        <span class="text-red-500/80">●</span> location &nbsp;
        <span class="text-orange-500/80">●</span> identity / time &nbsp;
        <span class="text-base-content/30">●</span> camera settings
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="text-xs text-base-content/40 italic">
      The GPS coordinates above resolve to the Eiffel Tower. Anyone with this
      file now knows where you were on your last vacation.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Why it matters -->
  <section id="why-it-matters" class="w-full flex flex-col gap-4">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
      Why it's a privacy problem
    </h2>
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-3">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 p-4">
        <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1">
          Your home address, extracted from photos
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-base-content/55 leading-relaxed">
          A photo taken at home and shared online embeds your precise
          coordinates. Anyone can look up those coordinates in a maps app to
          identify where it was taken. This is how people leak their home
          address.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 p-4">
        <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1">
          Serial numbers link your identities
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-base-content/55 leading-relaxed">
          Device serial numbers embedded in EXIF data are unique and permanent.
          If you post photos under different accounts from the same device, a
          common serial number can link those identities.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 p-4">
        <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1">
          Timestamps build a timeline of your movements
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-base-content/55 leading-relaxed">
          A series of photos with accurate timestamps and location data can
          reveal where you were and when. Given enough data points, a malicious
          actor could reconstruct a precise timeline, or even your daily and
          weekly routines.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How StripMeta works -->
  <section id="how-it-removes" class="w-full flex flex-col gap-4">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">How <Brand /> removes it</h2>
    <p class="text-base-content/65 leading-relaxed">
      Most metadata removal tools send your files to a server. <Brand /> never does.
      All processing runs directly in your browser using the same APIs your device
      uses — your files stay on your device from start to finish.
    </p>
    <p class="text-base-content/65 leading-relaxed">
      Rather than re-encoding images (which would degrade quality), <Brand /> performs
      surgical removal at the binary level for <a
        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JPEG"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        class="underline underline-offset-2 decoration-base-content/30 hover:decoration-base-content/60 transition-colors"
        >JPEG</a
      >, <a
        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PNG"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        class="underline underline-offset-2 decoration-base-content/30 hover:decoration-base-content/60 transition-colors"
        >PNG</a
      >, and <a
        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WebP"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        class="underline underline-offset-2 decoration-base-content/30 hover:decoration-base-content/60 transition-colors"
        >WebP</a
      > files. EXIF segments, PNG metadata chunks, and WebP <a
        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resource_Interchange_File_Format"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        class="underline underline-offset-2 decoration-base-content/30 hover:decoration-base-content/60 transition-colors"
        >RIFF</a
      > metadata containers are identified and excised from the file structure directly,
      leaving the compressed image data completely untouched. The result is an identical-quality
      image with no metadata. For formats that don't support lossless stripping —
      such as GIF, TIFF, or AVIF — and when <em>Paranoid mode</em> is enabled in settings,
      <Brand /> falls back to re-encoding through the browser's canvas API, which
      guarantees complete removal at the cost of a small quality reduction and conversion
      to JPEG.
    </p>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-3 gap-3 text-center">
      <div
        class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 p-4 flex flex-col items-center gap-2"
      >
        <span class="text-2xl">🔬</span>
        <p class="font-semibold text-sm">Lossless for JPEG, PNG, WebP</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-base-content/50">
          Image data is never re-encoded. Only metadata containers are removed.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div
        class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 p-4 flex flex-col items-center gap-2"
      >
        <span class="text-2xl">🔒</span>
        <p class="font-semibold text-sm">Zero uploads</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-base-content/50">
          No file ever leaves your browser. There is no server to receive it.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div
        class="rounded-xl border border-base-300 p-4 flex flex-col items-center gap-2"
      >
        <span class="text-2xl">⚡</span>
        <p class="font-semibold text-sm">Batch processing</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-base-content/50">
          Drop an entire folder. All files are processed and zipped for
          download.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Step by step guide -->
  <section id="how-to-use" class="w-full flex flex-col gap-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">How to use StripMeta</h2>

    <!-- Step 1 -->
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
        <span
          class="w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-teal-500/15 text-teal-600 dark:text-teal-400 text-sm font-bold flex items-center justify-center shrink-0"
          >1</span
        >
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
          Open StripMeta and add your photos
        </h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-base-content/60 text-sm leading-relaxed pl-10">
        Go to <a
          href="/"
          class="underline underline-offset-2 text-teal-600 dark:text-teal-400"
          >stripmeta.info</a
        >. Drag and drop photos directly onto the page, click <strong
          >Select files</strong
        > to pick individual images, or use <strong>Open folder</strong> to load an
        entire directory at once. JPEG, PNG, WebP, TIFF, HEIC, and more are all accepted.
      </p>
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-base-300 overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
        <div
          class="flex items-center px-3 py-2 bg-base-200 border-b border-base-300"
        >
          <div
            class="flex-1 bg-base-300/60 rounded-full py-0.5 px-3 text-[0.6rem] text-base-content/30 text-center"
          >
            stripmeta.info
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-base-100 p-3">
          <div
            class="flex items-center justify-between py-2 px-1 mb-3 border-b border-base-200"
          >
            <span class="text-sm font-extrabold brand-name">StripMeta</span>
            <span class="text-[0.6rem] text-base-content/30"
              >Remove photo metadata — privately.</span
            >
          </div>
          <div
            class="border-2 border-dashed border-base-300 rounded-xl py-8 px-4 flex flex-col items-center gap-2 text-center"
          >
            <svg
              class="text-base-content/25"
              width="28"
              height="28"
              viewBox="0 0 24 24"
              fill="none"
              stroke="currentColor"
              stroke-width="1.5"
            >
              <path
                stroke-linecap="round"
                stroke-linejoin="round"
                d="M3 16l4-4 4 4 4-6 4 6"></path>
              <rect
                x="3"
                y="3"
                width="18"
                height="18"
                rx="2"
                stroke-linecap="round"
                stroke-linejoin="round"></rect>
            </svg>
            <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-base-content/80">
              Drop photos or folders here
            </p>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mt-1">
              <span
                class="btn btn-xs btn-outline pointer-events-none text-[0.6rem] h-6 min-h-0"
                >Select files</span
              >
              <span class="text-[0.6rem] text-base-content/30">or</span>
              <span
                class="btn btn-xs btn-outline pointer-events-none text-[0.6rem] h-6 min-h-0"
                >📁 Open folder</span
              >
            </div>
            <p class="text-[0.6rem] text-base-content/35 mt-1">
              JPEG, PNG, WebP, TIFF, HEIC and more
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Step 2 -->
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
        <span
          class="w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-teal-500/15 text-teal-600 dark:text-teal-400 text-sm font-bold flex items-center justify-center shrink-0"
          >2</span
        >
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">Review what was found</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-base-content/60 text-sm leading-relaxed pl-10">
        StripMeta scans each file and shows you what metadata it detected — GPS
        data, timestamps, device information. Files with no metadata are flagged
        separately. Click any file to inspect its full metadata before
        stripping.
      </p>
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-base-300 overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
        <div
          class="flex items-center px-3 py-2 bg-base-200 border-b border-base-300"
        >
          <div
            class="flex-1 bg-base-300/60 rounded-full py-0.5 px-3 text-[0.6rem] text-base-content/30 text-center"
          >
            stripmeta.info
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-base-100 p-3 flex flex-col gap-2">
          <div class="flex items-center justify-between px-1 mb-0.5">
            <span
              class="text-[0.6rem] font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-base-content/35"
              >Files</span
            >
            <span class="text-[0.6rem] text-base-content/30">3 files</span>
          </div>
          {
            [
              {
                name: "vacation.jpg",
                size: "3.2 MB",
                badges: [
                  ["📍 GPS", "text-red-500/80 bg-red-500/8 border-red-500/20"],
                  [
                    "📅 Date",
                    "text-blue-500/80 bg-blue-500/8 border-blue-500/20",
                  ],
                  [
                    "📱 iPhone 15",
                    "text-base-content/40 bg-base-200 border-base-300",
                  ],
                ],
              },
              {
                name: "selfie.jpg",
                size: "2.1 MB",
                badges: [
                  ["📍 GPS", "text-red-500/80 bg-red-500/8 border-red-500/20"],
                  [
                    "📅 Date",
                    "text-blue-500/80 bg-blue-500/8 border-blue-500/20",
                  ],
                ],
              },
              {
                name: "document.png",
                size: "480 KB",
                badges: [
                  [
                    "📅 Date",
                    "text-blue-500/80 bg-blue-500/8 border-blue-500/20",
                  ],
                  [
                    "🖥 Lightroom",
                    "text-base-content/40 bg-base-200 border-base-300",
                  ],
                ],
              },
            ].map(({ name, size, badges }) => (
              <div class="flex items-center gap-2 px-3 py-2 rounded-xl border border-base-300 bg-base-100">
                <div class="w-8 h-8 rounded-lg bg-base-200 shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center">
                  <svg
                    class="w-4 h-4 text-base-content/25"
                    viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                    fill="none"
                    stroke="currentColor"
                    stroke-width="1.5"
                  >
                    <path
                      stroke-linecap="round"
                      stroke-linejoin="round"
                      d="M3 16l4-4 4 4 4-6 4 6"
                    />
                    <rect
                      x="3"
                      y="3"
                      width="18"
                      height="18"
                      rx="2"
                      stroke-linecap="round"
                      stroke-linejoin="round"
                    />
                  </svg>
                </div>
                <div class="flex-1 min-w-0">
                  <p class="text-xs font-medium truncate">{name}</p>
                  <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-1 mt-1">
                    {badges.map(([label, cls]) => (
                      <span
                        class={`text-[0.55rem] font-medium px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded-full border ${cls}`}
                      >
                        {label}
                      </span>
                    ))}
                    <span class="btn btn-xs btn-ghost pointer-events-none text-[0.55rem] h-5 min-h-0 px-1.5 text-base-content/40">
                      View details
                    </span>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <span class="text-[0.6rem] text-base-content/30 shrink-0">
                  {size}
                </span>
              </div>
            ))
          }
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Step 3 -->
